hypothesis: Zero-conversion domains (89% experiment→lesson loss) contain harvestable insights in batch experiment sequences. Targeted extraction should reduce loss.
method: Fan-out 3 agents to explore experiments in history (46), game-theory (22), statistics (21). Each scanned 8-12 experiment JSONs for verdict/finding/diff fields. Extracted transferable rules and cross-domain isomorphisms.

themes.L-578: Volume-conversion paradox: batch sequences hide accumulated patterns, need harvest checkpoints
themes.L-575: Simpsons Paradox in protocol adoption: contracts attract harder work, stratify before comparing
themes.L-576: Regime splitting prerequisite: I2>50% heterogeneity means split before null declaration

results.conversion_improvement: 3 lessons from 89 experiments in 3 zero-conv domains = 3.4% partial recovery

cross_domain_isomorphisms: ISO-13 anti-windup: L-556 (stale baseline), L-572 (archive blindness), L-574 (batch extraction failure) — same class: working mechanism + broken feedback channel
ISO-23 regime-crossover: L-576 (canceling subgroups average to null) connects to L-573 (strategy regimes) and regime-dependent dispatch
ISO-4 causality recognition: L-575 (selection confound in voluntary protocol adoption) — protocols adopted for hard tasks look worse in aggregate
verdict: CONFIRMED: zero-conversion domains contain rich harvestable insights. Volume-conversion paradox explained: batch sweeps produce incremental individual experiments that dont trigger lesson extraction. Fix: explicit harvest checkpoints every 5th domain experiment.
diff: Expected >=3 lessons, got exactly 3. Cross-domain ISO connections (3 found) were richer than expected. Still ~85% of zero-conv experiments unprocessed — partial harvest only.
next_steps: Require candidate_lesson_id field in experiment JSON template
Add harvest checkpoint to orient.py: warn when domain has 5+ experiments and 0 lessons
Rerun F-IS7 edge measurement at S360 to measure conversion rate change
Deeper harvest of history (46 exp) and remaining game-theory experiments
